definition.value: A poly(ethylene glycol) compound having a methacrylate group at the alpha-terminus and a hydroxyl group at the omega-terminus.
A poly(ethylene glycol) derivative that is poly(ethylene glycol) in which one of the terminal hydroxy groups has been acylated by formal condensation with methacrylic acid.
A sulfonamide consisting of pyrimidine having a methoxy substituent at the 5-position and a 4-aminobenzenesulfonamido group at the 2-position.
The betaine obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxylic acid group to the amino group of L-aspartic acid 4-semialdehyde.
The methanesulfonate trihydrate salt of ziprasidone.
A glycol that is a derivative of glycerol in which one of the hydroxy groups is replaced by an anilino group.
A poly(ethylene glycol) derivative that is poly(ethylene glycol) in which one of the terminal hydroxy groups has been converted to the corresponding p-nonylphenyl ether.
A polymer consisting of nonylbenzene with a poly(ethylene glycol) moiety attached at position 4.
A tergitol polymer consisting of nonylbenzene with a nine-membered poly(ethylene glycol) moiety attached at position 4.
A monocarboxylic acid that consists of phenylacetic acid bearing iodo, hydroxy and nitro substituents at positions 3, 4 and 5 respectively.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion comprising hexanoate substituted at C-2 and C-4 with oxo and hydroxy groups respectively.
A dipeptide composed of two L-glutamic acid units joined by a peptide linkage.
A glycol that is butane-1,4-diol substituted at the 2- and 3-positions by (1,3-benzodioxol-5-yl)methyl groups (the R,R-configuration).
An alpha-D-galactopyranoside having a 4-nitrophenyl substituent at the anomeric position.
The ester formed between N-hydroxysuccinimide and (4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetic acid.
The ester formed between N-hydroxysuccinimide and (4-hydroxy-5-iodo-3-nitrophenyl)acetic acid.
A parenteral third-generation cephalosporin, bearing a 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino group at the 7beta-position.
The trihydrate of morphine hydrochloride.
An imidazolidine containing one or more oxo groups.
Oxazoles in which the N and O atoms are adjacent.
A ketone containing an hydroxy group on the beta-carbon relative to the C=O group.
A phosphocholine that is the 4-nitrophenyl ester of choline phosphate.
A D-galactosamine 1-phosphate compound having an N-acetyl substituent.
The beta-anomer of N-acetyl-D-galactosamine 1-phosphate.

Any member of the cephamycin sub-group of cephem antibiotics, differing from cephalosporins in possessing a methoxy group at the 7alpha-position of the cephem nucleus, and in being resistant to beta-lactamase.
A 1-O-alkyl-2-O-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the alkyl group is specified as hexadecyl.

A cephalosporin with  acetoxymethyl and 2(pyridin-4-ylsulfanyl)acetamido substituents at positions 3 and 7, respectively, of the cephem skeleton. It is used (as its sodium salt) as an antibiotic, being effective against gram-negative and gram-positive organisms.
A disaccharide formed between beta-D-galactose and D-gluconic acid.
A mucopolysaccharide consisting of dermatan with sulfate substituents at the 6'-position of the N-acetylgalactosamines.
An N-sulfonated monobactam antibiotic.
A second generation cephalosporin antibiotic.

A third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic, bearing a 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino group at the 7beta-position and a [(1-methyl-1H-tetrazol-5-yl)sulfanyl]methyl group at the 3-position.
An aminopyrimidine in which the pyrimidine ring bears amino and hydroxy substituents at positions 2 and 4, respectively.

Any member of a group of synthetic antibiotics, similar to cephems but with carbon substituted for the sulfur; all possessing an acylated amine functionality at C-6 and (S,R) stereochemistry at C-6 and C-7.
Any member of the oxacephem sub-group of cephem antibiotics, in which the thiaazabicyclo moiety of the cephalosporins is replaced by an oxaazabicyclo moiety, and  where R3 is -H or -OCH3.
An alpha-D-galactoside having a methyl substituent at the anomeric position.
A keto-disaccharide consisting of alpha,alpha-trehalose with the keto group at the 3-position.

Any one of a large family of chemically related mycotoxins with a structure based on a sesquiterpene skeleton. The most important structural features causing the biological activities of trichothecenes are a 12,13-epoxy ring, the presence of hydroxy or acetyl groups at appropriate positions on the trichothecene nucleus and the structure and position of the side-chain.
A pyruvic acid having a 5-benzyloxyindol-3-yl group at the 3-position.
The anion of 3-(5-benzyloxyindol-3-yl)pyruvic acid.

A valeric acid derivative having an (R)-hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and an (S)-methyl substituent at the 3-position; one of 4 steroisomers of 2-hydroxy-3-methylpentanoic acid, generated by isoleucine metabolism. Found at significantly higher levels than normal in patients with maple syrup urine disease (MSUD).
The conjugate base of (2R,3S)-2-hydroxy-3-methylpentanoic acid.
A sulfonamide antibiotic in which 4-aminobenzenesulfonic acid and 4,5-dimethyl-1,3-oxazol-2-amine have combined to form the sulfonamide bond.
An antifungal macrolactone antibiotic, obtained from Diheterospora chlamydosporia and Chaetomium chiversii that inhibits protein tyrosine kinase and heat shock protein 90 (Hsp90).
The pivaloyloxymethyl ester prodrug of cefditoren.
An azabicycloalkane compound having angelyloxy and echimidinyloxymethyl substituents attached to the ring system.
A compound having the general formula RR'C(OH)OR'' (R'' =/= H).
